ATTACHMENT A Rate Schedule FERC No. 1 Riverstart Solar Park LLC Reactive Power Compensation
RIVERSTART SOLAR PARK LLC
RATE SCHEDULE FERC NO. 1
Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service
Riverstart Solar Park LLC ("Riverstart") provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service ("Reactive Supply Service") from the Riverstart generating facility ("Riverstart Facility").
The Riverstart Facility is a solar generating facility that is interconnected to transmission facilities owned by AEP Indiana Michigan Transmission Company and under the operational control of the PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM").
This Rate Schedule FERC No. 1 sets forth Riverstart's revenue requirement for Reactive Supply Service from the Riverstart Facility. This Rate Schedule shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
Riverstart's monthly fixed revenue requirement consists of the charge for the Fixed Capability Component. Payment to Riverstart shall be subject to Schedule 2 of PJM's Open Access Transmission Tariff.
MONTHLY REVENUE REQUIREMENT:
The Annual Reactive Service Revenue Requirement is: $2,316,624.79. The Monthly Reactive Service Revenue Requirement is: $193,052.07.

UNITED STATES OF AMERICA BEFORE THE FEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION
Riverstart Solar Park LLC ) Docket No. ER24-1454-___
MOTION OF RIVERSTART SOLAR PARK LLC FOR AUTHORIZATION TO IMPLEMENT SETTLEMENT RATE ON AN INTERIM BASIS, REQUEST TO WAIVE ANSWER PERIOD, AND REQUEST FOR EXPEDITED TREATMENT
To: The Honorable Andrew Satten Chief Administrative Law Judge
cc: The Honorable Patricia E. Hurt Administrative Law Judge
Pursuant to Rule 212 of the Rules of Practice and Procedure of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (Commission), 18 C.F.R. § 385.212 (2023). Riverstart Solar Park LLC (Riverstart) respectfully requests authorization to place the settlement rates that have been offered in these proceedings into effect on an interim basis, effective October 1, 2024, pending Commission review and approval or acceptance of a settlement. Riverstart is filing an Offer of Settlement concurrently in this docket. Riverstart further requests, with respect to this Motion, that the Chief Administrative Law Judge (Chief Judge) waive the answer period and grant expedited treatment, and issue an order granting this Motion as soon as possible. As described below, granting this Motion will not prejudice the interest of any party to these proceedings, and is in the public interest as it permits reduced settlement rates to be placed into effect pending Commission review and approval or acceptance of a settlement. I. BACKGROUND Riverstart owns and operates a 200 MWac solar electric generating facility (Riverstart Facility). The Riverstart Facility achieved commercial operation on December 28, 2021. The Riverstart Facility is interconnected with the transmission system of AEP Indiana Michigan Transmission Company (IM Transco), within the PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (PJM) region. Riverstart, IM Transco, and PJM are parties to an interconnection service agreement (ISA). On March 12, 2024, Riverstart submitted a proposed rate schedule (Rate Schedule) setting forth the Riverstart Facility for Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service (Reactive Service), as defined in Schedule 2 of the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff (OATT). The Independent Market Monitor (IMM) for PJM, American Electric Power Service Corporation (AEP), and American Municipal Power, Inc. (AMP) timely intervened in the proceeding. (Doc-less) Motion to Intervene of the Independent Market Monitor for PJM, Docket No. ER24-1424-000 (Mar. 13, 2024); (Doc-less) Motion to Intervene of American Electric Power Service Corporation, Docket No. ER24-1424-000 (Mar. 18, 2024); (Doc-less) Motion to Intervene of American Municipal Power, Inc., Docket No. ER24-1424-000 (Apr. 2, 2024); Comments of American Municipal Power, Inc., Docket No. ER24-1424-000 (Apr. 2, 2024).
On May 9, 2024, the Commission accepted Rate Schedule for filing and suspended for a nominal period, to become effective on March 13, 2024, and set the filing for hearing and settlement judge procedures. Riverstart Solar Park LLC, 187 FERC ¶ 61,070 (2024).
The Chief Judge designated Administrative Law Judge Patricia E. Hurt as the settlement judge in these proceedings. With the assistance of Judge Hurt, Riverstart, the IMM, AMP, and Commission Trial Staff (Trial Staff) actively engaged in settlement discussions. The parties ultimately reached an agreement on a black box basis that resolves all issues set for hearing, as well as all of the issues raised during settlement discussions, in the above captioned proceedings. AEP does not oppose the Settlement.
II. MOTION TO IMPLEMENT SETTLEMENT RATE ON AN INTERIM BASIS As noted above, Riverstart, the IMM, AMP, and Trial Staff have reached an agreement that will resolve all issues set for hearing in the Order. Among the items agreed to is the reduction of Riverstarts currently effective annual revenue requirement from $ 2,316,624.79 to $439,800. Riverstarts revised Reactive Power rate schedule, which shows the rate reduction, is attached hereto as Attachment A. As noted in footnote 2 of the transmittal letter accompanying the Offer of Settlement, this motion for interim rates includes the live tariff records reflecting the Settlement Reactive Power rate schedule.
In order for ratepayers to realize as soon as possible the benefits of the reduced rates agreed to among the parties, and so that Riverstart and PJM may implement the Settlement Power rate schedule beginning October 1, 2024, Riverstart is filing this Motion for authorization to implement the Settlement Reactive Power rate schedule on an interim basis, subject to refund or surcharge, with interest computed in accordance with 18 C.F.R. § 35.19a, pending Commission review of the Settlement. In accordance with the Settlement, Riverstart respectfully requests that the Chief Judge grant this Motion permitting them to implement the Settlement Reactive Power rate schedule on an interim basis, effective as of October 1, 2024, pending Commission action on a settlement filed in these proceedings. The action requested by Riverstart is consistent with the approved implementation of settlement rates on an interim basis in other proceedings. See, e.g., Moxie Freedom LLC, 167 FERC ¶ 63,014 (2019); Logan Generating Co., L.P., 158 FERC ¶ 63,005 (2017); All Dams Generation, LLC, 157 FERC ¶ 63,029 (2016); Cottonwood Energy Co. LP, 149 FERC ¶ 63,011 (2014); Calpine Mid Merit, LLC, 142 FERC ¶ 63,010 (2013).
The IMM, AEP, AMP, and Trial Staff have authorized Riverstart to represent that they do not oppose this Motion. III. REQUEST FOR WAIVERS AND EXPEDITED TREATMENT The Commission may, for good cause shown, permit a public utility to collect a rate different than the rate schedule on file with the Commission. 18 C.F.R. § 35.1(e). Further, Rule 307(a)(1)(iv) of the Commissions Revised General Rules authorizes the Chief Judge to act on uncontested motions that would result in lower interim settlement rates, pending Commission action on settlement agreements. Id. § 375.307(a)(1)(iv). Implementation of the Settlement Reactive Power rate schedule on an interim basis will enable ratepayers to realize the benefit, without delay, of the reduced rates under the forthcoming settlement. Accordingly, good cause exists to grant this unopposed Motion to make the Settlement Reactive Power rate schedule, effective as of October 1, 2024, on an interim basis. Riverstart respectfully requests expedited action on this Motion to allow sufficient time for PJM to implement the Settlement Reactive Power rate schedule as soon as possible. Riverstart further requests waiver of the answer period on this Motion, and requests any other necessary waivers of the Commissions regulations, including the Commissions prior notice requirements, to the extent necessary to permit the Settlement Reactive Power rate schedule to be implemented on an interim basis. IV. CONCLUSION WHEREFORE, for the foregoing reasons, Riverstart respectfully requests that the Chief Judge permit the Settlement Reactive Power rate schedule to be made effective on an interim basis, pending Commission approval or acceptance of the Settlement. Respectfully submitted,
/s/ Suzanne Keppeler McBride Van Ness Feldman, LLP 2000 Pennsylvania Avenue, NW Suite 6000 Washington, DC 20006 202-298-1927 skm@vnf.com
Counsel for Riverstart Solar Park LLC
Dated: October 8, 2024
